A ranking of NFL kickers for the 2019-2020 season using R, Stan and Geometry

James R Bland (https://sites.google.com/site/jamesbland/)

February 4, 2020

A few months ago, I developed and estimated a model for field goal attempts in American Football. As the 2019-2020 NFL season has ended, I figured I would re-visit this model, and use this most recent season’s data to generate some player rankings.

I modified my code from this blog post to download every NFL field goal attempt this season, as recorded by pro-football-reference.com.

Here is a summary of what I downloaded (more details in the previous blog post):

AggData<-aggregate(Data[,c("Dist","Y","B")],by=list(Data$Dist),FUN=mean)

AggData$count<-aggregate(Data[,c("Dist")], by=list(Data$Dist),FUN=length)$x
#AggData<-AggData[AggData$Dist<=65,]
plt<-ggplot(AggData,aes(x=Dist,y=Y,size=count))+geom_smooth(method="loess")+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")+geom_point(alpha=0.5)+ylim(0,1)

Model

This model is the same model I used in my original post, but I put these details in here so that we are all on the same page.

A player makes a field goal attempt \(x\) yards from the goal (my data). The goal posts are \(d\) yards apart (given), and the crossbar is \(h\) yards above the ground (I attempted to use this too, but there are not enough long shots to identify the parameters for this model, see Appendix II).

Let \(y\) be the hypotenuse of the right-angled triangle made between the ball, the midpoint of the goalposts, and one of the goal posts. This hypotenuse has length: \(y=\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}\). The angle at the ball vertex of this triangle can be found by solving: \[ \begin{aligned} x&=y\cos\theta\\ x&=\cos\theta\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}\\ \cos\theta&=\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\\ \theta&=\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\right) \end{aligned} \] And hence the angle of tolerance for a field goal at the \(x\)-yard line is \(\pm\theta\).

Now suppose that the actual angle of a kick, where \(\theta=0\) corresponds to a straight kick, is distributed \(N(0,\kappa)\). The probability of getting the angle right on a kick is therefore: \[ \Pr\left(\text{angle good} \mid x,\kappa\right)=1-2\Phi\left(-\kappa^{-1}\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\right)\right) \]

This model has one parameter, \(\kappa\), which must be positive. I use \(\log\kappa \sim N(\log(0.1),1)\) the prior. The prior is the only difference between this and my previous applications. I am using my understanding of what a reasonable value for \(\kappa\) is, and then adding a relatively huge variance to my actual understanding.

Estimating the model in Stan

// FieldGoalsCountLogNormal.stan
functions {
   
              
}
data {
  // Tell Stan how to read in the data
  int n; // Number of observations
  vector[n] Angle; 
  int y[n]; // =count of scored
  int N[n]; // number of attempts from that distance
  real priorK[2];
  
}
transformed data {
    
}
parameters {
  real<lower=0> k;

}
transformed parameters {
  
}
model {
    vector[n] p;
    k ~ lognormal(priorK[1],priorK[2]);
    
    
    for (ii in 1:n) {
        p[ii] =  1-2*normal_cdf((-Angle[ii]),0.0,k);
        
    }   


  y ~ binomial(N,p);


  }
generated quantities {

}

Fitting the model to pooled data

Assuming that all kickers are equally accurate, Stan gives me a posterior distribution like this:

  ksim<-extract(FitALL)$k
  plt<-ggplot()+geom_density(aes(x=ksim))
  plt<-plt+xlab("\u03BA")+theme_bw()
  plt

But it is somewhat more useful to look at the model’s predictions of success as a function of distance:

  x<- seq(1,70,1)
  angle<-acos(x/sqrt(x^2+d^2/4))
  pm <- x
  pl <- x
  pr <- x
  for (xx in 1:length(x)) {
    psim<-1-2*pnorm(-angle[xx],0,ksim)
    pm[xx]<-mean(psim)
    pl[xx]<-quantile(psim,probs=0.025)
    pr[xx]<-quantile(psim,probs=0.975)
  }
  data<-data.frame(x,pm,pl,pr)
  
  plt<-ggplot()+geom_line(data=data,aes(x=x,y=pm),color="blue")
  plt<-plt+geom_ribbon(data=data,aes(x=x,ymin=pl,ymax=pr),linetype="blank",fill="blue",alpha=0.5)
  plt<-plt+geom_point(data=AggData,aes(x=Dist,y=Y,size=count),alpha=0.5)
  plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")+ylim(0,1)
  plt<-plt+theme_bw()
  plt

So not a particularly good fit, but my main point of this was to do player rankings, so here we go …

Player rankings

I estimated the model on each kicker separately, excluding those who made fewer that 5 attempts. Here are the rankings based on posterior mean \(\kappa\) (smaller is better):

  PlayerK<-aggregate(SimPlayer[,c("k","Attempts","SuccessRate")],by=list(SimPlayer$Player),FUN=mean)
  # add in credible regions
  kl<-aggregate(SimPlayer[,c("k")],by=list(SimPlayer$Player),FUN= function(x) quantile(x,0.025))
  kr<-aggregate(SimPlayer[,c("k")],by=list(SimPlayer$Player),FUN= function(x) quantile(x,0.975))
  PlayerK$kl<-kl$x
  PlayerK$kr<-kr$x
  PlayerK$LastName<-sub(".* ","",PlayerK$Group.1)
  PlayerK[order(PlayerK$k),c("Group.1","k","SuccessRate","Attempts","kl","kr")]

So here I have sorted by posterior mean \(\kappa\), but also show each player’s number of attempts, and “Success Rate”, which is the average success, unconditional of distance. These rankings do not line up exactly:

  plt<-ggplot(data=PlayerK,aes(y=rank(1/SuccessRate),x=rank(k),label=LastName))+geom_point(aes(size=1/(kr-kl)))+theme_bw()+geom_abline(intercept=0,slope=1)
  plt<-plt+xlab("\u03BA ranking (lower is better)")+ylab("Ranking using unconditional success rates")
  plt

That is, on the horizontal axis I have my own rankings based on \(\kappa\) (lower is better), and on the vertical axis I just have the average success rate for that player. I also show how certain I am about \(\kappa\) by making the dot size inversely proportional to the size of the 95% credible region on \(\kappa\) (i.e. larger means more certain).

It is a bit hard to see the player names associated with these dots if I overlay them on the above plot, so here they are:

  plt<-ggplot(data=PlayerK,aes(y=rank(1/SuccessRate),x=rank(k),label=LastName))+geom_text()+theme_bw()
  plt<-plt+xlab("\u03BA ranking (lower is better)")+ylab("Ranking using unconditional success rates")+geom_abline(intercept=0,slope=1)
  plt

The way to read this is that, for example, that Gostkowski looks much better using the unconditional success rate than if one used my estimates of \(\kappa\).

And finally, because I am a sucker for animated GIFs, here are the model’s predictions for each player individually:

PlayerK<-PlayerK[order(-PlayerK$k),]
GIFdata<-data.frame()
x<-seq(1,70)
for (ii in 1:dim(PlayerK)[1]) {
  pl<-1-2*pnorm(-angle,0,PlayerK[ii,]$kl)
  pr<-1-2*pnorm(-angle,0,PlayerK[ii,]$kr)
  p<-1-2*pnorm(-angle,0,PlayerK[ii,]$k)
  state<-paste(PlayerK[ii,]$Group.1,", \u03BA =",round(PlayerK[ii,]$k,4),", N =",PlayerK[ii,]$Attempts,", p =",round(PlayerK[ii,]$SuccessRate,2))
  tmp<-data.frame(x,pl,pr,state,p)
  GIFdata<-rbind(GIFdata,tmp)
}
  
  
  plt<-ggplot(data=GIFdata,aes(x=x,ymin=pl,ymax=pr,y=p))+geom_ribbon(linetype="blank",fill="blue",alpha=0.5)
  plt<-plt+geom_line(color="blue",size=2)
  plt<-plt+transition_states(state,transition_length=5,state_length=5)
  plt<-plt+labs(title = '{closest_state}')
  plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")+ylim(0,1)
  plt<-plt+theme_bw()

  animate(plt, nframes = 10*dim(PlayerK)[1])
